# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dali-lighting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] BAS functionality may keep a building's climate within a specified range, provide light to rooms based on occupancy, monitor performance and device failures, and provide malfunction alarms to building maintenance staff.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] A BAS works to reduce building energy and maintenance costs compared to a non-controlled building.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Most commercial, institutional, and industrial buildings built after 2000 include a BAS, whilst older buildings may be retrofitted with a new BAS.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] A building controlled by a BAS is often referred to as an "intelligent building", a "smart building", or (if a residence) a *smart home*.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Commercial and industrial buildings have historically relied on robust proven protocols (like BACnet) while proprietary protocols (like X-10) were used in homes.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] With the advent of wireless sensor networks and the Internet of Things, an increasing number of smart buildings are resorting to using low-power wireless communication technologies such as Zigbee, Bluetooth Low Energy and LoRa to interconnect the local sensors, actuators and processing devices.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Almost all multi-story green buildings are designed to accommodate a BAS for the energy, air and water conservation characteristics.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Electrical device demand response is a typical function of a BAS, as is the more sophisticated ventilation and humidity monitoring required of "tight" insulated buildings.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Most green buildings also use as many low-power DC devices as possible.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Even a passivhaus design intended to consume no net energy whatsoever will typically require a BAS to manage heat capture, shading and venting, and scheduling device use.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Building management systems are most commonly implemented in large projects with extensive mechanical, HVAC, and electrical systems.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Systems linked to a BMS typically represent 40% of a building's energy usage; if lighting is included, this number approaches to 70%.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] BMS systems are a critical component to managing energy demand.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Improperly configured BMS systems are believed to account for 20% of building energy usage, or approximately 8% of total energy usage in the United States.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] In addition to controlling the building's internal environment, BMS systems are sometimes linked to access control (turnstiles and access doors controlling who is allowed access and egress to the building) or other security systems such as closed-circuit television (CCTV) and motion detectors.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Fire alarm systems and elevators are also sometimes linked to a BMS for monitoring.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] In case a fire is detected then only the fire alarm panel could close dampers in the ventilation system to stop smoke spreading, shut down air handlers, start smoke evacuation fans, and send all the elevators to the ground floor and park them to prevent people from using them.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Building management systems have also included disaster-response mechanisms (such as base isolation) to save structures from earthquakes.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] In more recent times, companies and governments have been working to find similar solutions for flood zones and coastal areas at-risk to rising sea levels.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Self-adjusting floating environment draws from existing technologies used to float concrete bridges and runways such as Washington's SR 520 and Japan's Mega-Float.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Analog inputs are used to read a variable measurement.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Examples are temperature, humidity and pressure sensors which could be thermistor, 4–20 mA, 0–10 volt or platinum resistance thermometer (resistance temperature detector), or wireless sensors.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] A digital input indicates a device is on or off.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Some examples of digital inputs would be a door contact switch, a current switch, an air flow switch, or a voltage-free relay contact (dry contact).
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Digital inputs could also be pulse inputs counting the pulses over a period of time.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] An example is a turbine flow meter transmitting flow data as a frequency of pulses to an input.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Nonintrusive load monitoring is software relying on digital sensors and algorithms to discover appliance or other loads from electrical or magnetic characteristics of the circuit.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] It is however detecting the event by an analog means.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] These are extremely cost-effective in operation and useful not only for identification but to detect start-up transients, line or equipment faults, etc.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Occupancy sensors detect the presence, number, and sometimes location of people in a space to enable demand-controlled systems for lighting, HVAC, and energy management.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Traditional examples include passive infrared (PIR), ultrasonic, and CO2-based detectors, but advanced systems use low-resolution thermal imaging or area sensors to provide zone-level accuracy without capturing identifiable images, ensuring privacy compliance (e.g., GDPR).
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] These sensors output analog heat signatures or digital counts that integrate with building management systems via protocols like BACnet or wireless IoT networks, reducing energy use by up to 40% through precise ventilation and lighting control.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Analog outputs control the speed or position of a device, such as a variable frequency drive, an I-P (current to pneumatics) transducer, or a valve or damper actuator.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] An example is a hot water valve opening up 25% to maintain a setpoint.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Another example is a variable frequency drive ramping up a motor slowly to avoid a hard start.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Digital outputs are used to open and close relays and switches as well as drive a load upon command.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] An example would be to turn on the parking lot lights when a photocell indicates it is dark outside.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Another example would be to open a valve by allowing 24VDC/AC to pass through the output powering the valve.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Analog outputs could also be pulse type outputs emitting a frequency of pulses over a given period of time.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] An example is an energy meter calculating kWh and emitting a frequency of pulses accordingly.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Controllers are essentially small, purpose-built computers with input and output capabilities.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] These controllers come in a range of sizes and capabilities to control devices commonly found in buildings, and to control sub-networks of controllers.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Inputs allow a controller to read temperature, humidity, pressure, current flow, air flow, and other essential factors.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] The outputs allow the controller to send command and control signals to slave devices, and to other parts of the system.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Inputs and outputs can be either digital or analog.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Digital outputs are also sometimes called discrete depending on manufacturer.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Controllers used for building automation can be grouped in three categories: programmable logic controllers (PLCs), system/network controllers, and terminal unit controllers.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] However an additional device can also exist in order to integrate third-party systems (e.g. a stand-alone AC system) into a central building automation system.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Terminal unit controllers usually are suited for control of lighting and/or simpler devices such as a package rooftop unit, heat pump, VAV box, fan coil, etc.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] The installer typically selects one of the available pre-programmed personalities best suited to the device to be controlled, and does not have to create new control logic.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Occupancy is one of two or more operating modes for a building automation system; unoccupied, morning warmup, and night-time setback are other common modes.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Occupancy is usually based on time of day schedules.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] In occupancy mode, the BAS aims to provides a comfortable climate and adequate lighting, often with zone-based control so that users on one side of a building have a different thermostat (or a different system, or sub system) than users on the opposite side.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] A temperature sensor in the zone provides feedback to the controller, so it can deliver heating or cooling as needed.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] If enabled, morning warmup (MWU) mode occurs prior to occupancy.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] During morning warmup the BAS tries to bring the building to setpoint just in time for occupancy.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] The BAS often factors in outdoor conditions and historical experience to optimize MWU.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] This is also referred to as *optimized start*.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Some buildings rely on occupancy sensors to activate lighting or climate conditioning.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Given the potential for long lead times before a space becomes sufficiently cool or warm, climate conditioning is not often initiated directly by an occupancy sensor.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Lighting can be turned on, off, or dimmed with a building automation or lighting control system based on time of day, or on occupancy sensor, photosensors and timers.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] One typical example is to turn the lights in a space on for a half-hour since the last motion was sensed.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] A photocell placed outside a building can sense darkness, and the time of day, and modulate lights in outer offices and the parking lot.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Lighting is also a good candidate for demand response, with many control systems providing the ability to dim (or turn off) lights to take advantage of DR incentives and savings.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] In newer buildings, the lighting control can be based on the field bus Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI).
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Lamps with DALI ballasts are fully dimmable.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] DALI can also detect lamp and ballast failures on DALI luminaires and signals failures.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Shading and glazing are essential components in the building system, they affect occupants' visual, acoustical, and thermal comfort and provide the occupant with a view outdoor.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Automated shading and glazing systems are solutions for controlling solar heat gains and glare.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] It refers to the use of technology to control external or internal shading devices (such as blinds, and shades) or glazing itself.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] The system has an active and rapid response to various changing outdoor data (such as solar, wind) and to changing interior environment (such as temperature, illuminance, and occupant demands).
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Building shading and glazing systems can contribute to thermal and lighting improvement from both energy conservation and comfort point of view.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Dynamic shading devices allow the control of daylight and solar energy to enter into built environment in relation to outdoor conditions, daylighting demands and solar positions.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] The common products include venetian blinds, roller shades, louvers, and shutters.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] They are mostly installed on the interior side of the glazing system because of the low maintenance cost, but also can be used on the exterior or a combination of both.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Most air handlers mix return and outside air so less temperature/humidity conditioning is needed.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] This can save money by using less chilled or heated water (not all AHUs use chilled or hot water circuits).
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Some external air is needed to keep the building's air healthy.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] To optimize energy efficiency while maintaining healthy indoor air quality (IAQ), demand control (or controlled) ventilation (DCV) adjusts the amount of outside air based on measured levels of occupancy.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Analog or digital temperature sensors may be placed in the space or room, the return and supply air ducts, and sometimes the external air.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Actuators are placed on the hot and chilled water valves, the outside air and return air dampers.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] The supply fan (and return if applicable) is started and stopped based on either time of day, temperatures, building pressures or a combination.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] All modern building automation systems have alarm capabilities.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] It does little good to detect a potentially hazardous or costly situation if no one who can solve the problem is notified.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Notification can be through a computer (email or text message), pager, cellular phone voice call, audible alarm, or all of these.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] For insurance and liability purposes all systems keep logs of who was notified, when and how.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Alarms may immediately notify someone or only notify when alarms build to some threshold of seriousness or urgency.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] At sites with several buildings, momentary power failures can cause hundreds or thousands of alarms from equipment that has shut down – these should be suppressed and recognized as symptoms of a larger failure.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Some sites are programmed so that critical alarms are automatically re-sent at varying intervals.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] For example, a repeating critical alarm (of an uninterruptible power supply in 'bypass') might resound at 10 minutes, 30 minutes, and every 2 to 4 hours thereafter until the alarms are resolved.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Security systems can be interlocked to a building automation system.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] If occupancy sensors are present, they can also be used as burglar alarms.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Because security systems are often deliberately sabotaged, at least some detectors or cameras should have battery backup and wireless connectivity and the ability to trigger alarms when disconnected.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Modern systems typically use power-over-Ethernet (which can operate a pan-tilt-zoom camera and other devices up to 30–90 watts) which is capable of charging such batteries and keeps wireless networks free for genuinely wireless applications, such as backup communication in outage.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Fire alarm panels and their related smoke alarm systems are usually hard-wired to override building automation.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] For example: if the smoke alarm is activated, all the outside air dampers close to prevent air coming into the building, and an exhaust system can isolate the blaze.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Similarly, electrical fault detection systems can turn entire circuits off, regardless of the number of alarms this triggers or persons this distresses.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Fossil fuel combustion devices also tend to have their own over-rides, such as natural gas feed lines that turn off when slow pressure drops are detected (indicating a leak), or when excess methane is detected in the building's air supply.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] ASHRAE's open protocol BACnet or the open protocol LonTalk specify how most such devices interoperate.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Modern systems use SNMP to track events, building on decades of history with SNMP-based protocols in the computer networking world.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Physical connectivity between devices was historically provided by dedicated optical fiber, ethernet, ARCNET, RS-232, RS-485 or a low-bandwidth special purpose wireless network.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Modern systems rely on standards-based multi-protocol heterogeneous networking such as that specified in the IEEE 1905.1 standard and verified by the nVoy auditing mark.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Proprietary hardware dominates the controller market.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Each company has controllers for specific applications.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Some are designed with limited controls and no interoperability, such as simple packaged roof top units for HVAC.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Software will typically not integrate well with packages from other vendors.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Cooperation is at the Zigbee/BACnet/LonTalk level only.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Current systems provide interoperability at the application level, allowing users to mix-and-match devices from different manufacturers, and to provide integration with other compatible building control systems.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] These typically rely on SNMP, long used for this same purpose to integrate diverse computer networking devices into one coherent network.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] With the growing spectrum of capabilities and connections to the Internet of Things, building automation systems were repeatedly reported to be vulnerable, allowing hackers and cybercriminals to attack their components.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Buildings can be exploited by hackers to measure or change their environment: sensors allow surveillance (e.g. monitoring movements of employees or habits of inhabitants) while actuators allow to perform actions in buildings (e.g. opening doors or windows for intruders).
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] Several vendors and committees started to improve the security features in their products and standards, including KNX, Zigbee and BACnet (see recent standards or standard drafts).
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] However, researchers report several open problems in building automation security.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] On November 11, 2019, a 132-page security research paper was released titled "I Own Your Building (Management System)" by Gjoko Krstic and Sipke Mellema that addressed more than 100 vulnerabilities affecting various BMS and access control solutions by various vendors.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] On November 24, 2025, a 161-page security research paper was released titled "Project Brainfog: Beyond the Facade - Exposing Smart Giants" by Gjoko Krstic that addressed more than 1000 vulnerabilities affecting two widely used BAS controllers by ABB Group.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] It is common for room automation systems to employ a touchscreen as the primary way of controlling each operation.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] On November 27, 2018, a 29-page research paper titled "A Scalable Room Occupancy Prediction with Transferable Time Series Decomposition of CO2 Sensor Data" was published by Irvan Bastian Arief, Margaret Hamilton, and Flora Salim.
[src:dali-lighting/building-automation] The paper introduced a novel approach to leveraging carbon dioxide (CO2) sensor data to predict room occupancy—enabling smarter building automation by estimating the number of occupants in a room at any given time.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] DALI is specified by a series of technical standards in **IEC 62386**.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Standards conformance ensures that equipment from different manufacturers will interoperate.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The DALI trademark is allowed on devices that comply with the DiiA testing and certification requirements, and are listed as either registered (DALI version-1) or certified (DALI-2) on the DiiA website.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] D4i certification - an extension of DALI-2 - was added by DiiA in November 2019.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Members of the AG DALI were allowed to use the DALI trademark until the DALI working party was dissolved on 30 March 2017, when trademark use was transferred to DiiA members.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Since 9 June 2017, Digital Illumination Interface Alliance (DiiA) certifies DALI products.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] A DALI network consists of at least one application controller and bus power supply (which may be built into any of the products) as well as input devices (e.g. sensors and push-buttons), control gear (e.g., electrical ballasts, LED drivers and dimmers) with DALI interfaces.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Application controllers can control, configure or query each device by means of a bi-directional data exchange.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Unlike DMX, multiple controllers can co-exist on the bus.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The DALI protocol permits addressing devices individually, in groups or via broadcast.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Scenes can be stored in the devices, for recall on an individual, group or broadcast basis.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Groups and scenes are used to ensure simultaneous execution of level changes, since each packet requires about 25 ms - or 1.5 seconds if all 64 addresses were to change level.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Each device is assigned a unique short address between 0 and 63, making up to 64 devices possible in a basic system.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Address assignment is performed over the bus using a "commissioning" protocol built into the DALI controller, usually after all hardware is installed, or successively as devices are added.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The Device Address is commonly a LED driver with one or many LEDs sharing the same level.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] A DT6 driver is for single color temperature applications, a DT8 driver is used for CCT color tuning, or RGBWW multi color applications - for example a strip where all the "pixels" have the same color.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Data is transferred between devices by means of an asynchronous, half-duplex, serial protocol over a two-wire bus with a fixed data transfer rate of 1200 bit/s.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Collision detection is used to allow multiple transmitters on the bus.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] A single pair of wires comprises the bus used for communication on a DALI network.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The network can be arranged in bus or star topology, or a combination of these.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Each device on a DALI network can be addressed individually, unlike DSI and 0–10V devices.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Consequently, DALI networks typically use fewer wires than DSI or 0–10V systems.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The bus is used for both signal and bus power.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] A power supply provides a current limited source of up to 250 mA at typically 16 V DC; each device may draw up to 2 mA unless bus-powered.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] While many devices are mains-powered (line-powered), low-power devices such as motion detectors may be powered directly from the DALI bus.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Each device has a bridge rectifier on its input so it is polarity-insensitive.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The bus is a wired-AND configuration where signals are sent by briefly shorting the bus to a low voltage level.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Although the DALI control cable operates at ELV potential, it is not classified as SELV (*Safety* Extra Low Voltage) and therefore should not be Accessible to the user.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The requirements of the DALI standard IEC 62386-101 (clause 4.9.2) categorise the interface as FELV.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] It also requires that the interface have at least Basic insulation from AC mains, and Supplementary insulation from the interface to any user Accessible part like the cover of the equipment.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Clause 4.10 does not permit any part of the interface to be connected to Protective Earth unless this occurs at a low power (less than 250mA) bus power supply, or via a Class Y safety capacitor.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] This requirement for an unearthed interface precludes the use of an earthed conductor to meet the FELV requirements of IEC 60364-4-41 clause 411.7, further mandating the use of Basic insulation between AC mains and the interface.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] This also means that the interface cable is required to be mains-rated and permits it to be run next to mains cables or within a multi-core cable which includes mains power.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The network cable is required to provide a maximum drop of 2 volts along the cable.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] At 250 mA of supply current, that requires a resistance of ≤ 4 Ω per wire.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The wire size needed to achieve this depends on the length of the bus, up to a recommended maximum of 2.5 mm2 at 300 m when using the maximum rating of bus power supply.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The speed is kept low so no termination resistors are required, and data is transmitted using relatively high voltages (0±4.5 V for low and 16±6.5 V for high) enabling reliable communications in the presence of significant electrical noise.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Each bit is sent using Manchester encoding (a "1" bit is low for the first half of the bit time, and high for the second, while "0" is the reverse), so that power is present for half of each bit.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] When the bus is idle, the voltage level is continuously high (which is not the same as a data bit).
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Frames begin with a "1" start bit, then 8 to 32 data bits with the most significant bit first (standard RS-232 has the least significant bit first), followed by a minimum of 2.45 ms of idle.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] A DALI device, such as a LED driver, can be controlled individually via its short address.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Additionally, each DALI device may be members of one to 16 groups, or be a member of up to 16 scenes.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] All devices of a group respond to the commands addressed to the group.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] This method has the advantage of not requiring programming of group and scene information for each ballast.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The fade time of the transition can be chosen on the fly.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] If a large number of devices need to change at once, note that only 40 commands per second are possible - therefore, 64 individual addresses would require 1.5 seconds.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] For example, turning all lighting fixtures off may result in a visible delay between the first and last ballasts switching off.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] This issue is normally not a problem in rooms with a smaller number of ballasts.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] This method has the advantage of being immune to synchronization effects as described above.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] This method has the disadvantage of requiring each ballast to be programmed once, by a DALI master, with the required group numbers and scene information.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The fade time can still be configured on the fly, if required.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Devices store 16 programmable output levels as "scenes".
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Individual, Group or ALL devices can respond to a global Scene recall command to change to its previously configured level, e.g. dim lights over the audience and bright lights over the stage.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] A "system failure" level can be triggered by a loss of power (sustained low level) on the DALI bus, to provide a safe fallback if control is lost, a level of 255 excludes the device from this feature.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] DALI lighting levels are specified by an 8-bit value, with 0 representing off, 1 means 0.1% of full brightness, 254 means full brightness, and other values being logarithmically interpolated, giving a 2.77% increase per step.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] This is designed to match human eye sensitivity so that perceived brightness steps are uniform, and to ensure corresponding brightness levels in units from different manufacturers.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Forward frames sent to control gear are 16 bits long, comprising an address byte followed by an opcode byte.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The address byte specifies a target device or a *special command* addressed to all devices.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Except for special commands, when addressing a device, the 7 most significant bits is the device address.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The least significant bit of the address byte specifies the interpretation of the opcode byte, with "0" meaning that the opcode is a light level (ARC), and "1" meaning that the opcode is a command.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Multi packet commands are used for more complex tasks - like setting RGB colors.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] These commands use three "data transfer registers" (DTR, DTR1, DTR2 ) which can be read and written or used as a parameter by subsequent commands.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] For example, copy the current ARC level to DTR, save DTR as a scene.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Evidently, the DTR value can be different in different devices.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The DALI-2 standard added standardisation of control devices.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Control devices can include input devices such as daylight sensors, passive infrared room occupancy sensors, and manual lighting controls, or they can be application controllers that are the "brains" of the system - using information to make decisions and control the lights and other devices.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Control devices can also combine the functionality of an application controller and an input device.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Control devices use 24-bit forward frames, which are ignored by control gear, so up to 64 control devices may share the bus with up to 64 control gear.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] DiiA published several new specifications in 2018 and 2019, extending DALI-2 functionality with power and data, especially for intra-luminaire DALI systems.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Applications include indoor and outdoor luminaires, and small DALI systems.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The D4i trademark is used on certified products to indicate that these new features are included in the products.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] IEC 62386-209 describes colour control gear.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] This describes several colour types - methods of controlling colour.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] The most popular of these is Tc (tunable white), and was added to DALI-2 certification in January 2020.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] IEC 62386-202 describes self-contained emergency lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Features include automated triggering of function tests and duration tests, and recording of results.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] These devices are currently included in DALI version-1 registration, with tests for DALI-2 certification in development.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] Such DALI version-1 products can be mixed with DALI-2 products in the same system, with no problems expected.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] IEC 62386-104 describes several wireless and wired transport alternatives to the conventional wired DALI bus system.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] DiiA is working with other industry associations to enable certification of DALI-2 products that operate over certain underlying wireless carriers.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] It is also possible to combine DALI with wireless communication via application gateways that translate between DALI and the wireless protocol of choice.
[src:dali-lighting/digital-addressable-lighting-interface] While such gateways are not standardized, DiiA is working with other industry associations to develop the necessary specifications and tests to achieve this.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] A **dimmer** is a device connected to a light fixture and used to lower the brightness of the light.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] By changing the voltage waveform applied to the lamp, it is possible to lower the intensity of the light output.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Although variable-voltage devices are used for various purposes, the term *dimmer* is generally reserved for those intended to control light output from resistive incandescent, halogen, and (more recently) compact fluorescent lamps (CFLs) and light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] More specialized equipment is needed to dim fluorescent, mercury-vapor, solid-state, and other arc lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Dimmers range in size from small units the size of domestic light switches to high-power units used in large theatrical or architectural lighting installations.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Small domestic dimmers are generally directly controlled, although remote control systems (such as X10) are available.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Modern professional dimmers are generally controlled by a digital control system like DMX or DALI.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In newer systems, these protocols are often used in conjunction with Ethernet.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In the professional lighting industry, changes in intensity are called "fades" and can be "fade up" or "fade down".
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Dimmers with direct manual control had a limit on the speed they could be varied at but this problem has been largely eliminated with modern digital units (although very fast changes in brightness may still be avoided for other reasons like lamp life).
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Modern dimmers are built from semiconductors instead of variable resistors, because they have higher efficiency.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] A variable resistor would dissipate power as heat and acts as a voltage divider.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Since semiconductor or solid-state dimmers switch quickly between a low resistance "on" state and a high resistance "off" state, they dissipate very little power compared with the controlled load.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Most recently, software programmable internal dimmers can use signals from the same switch that turns lights on and off to control dimming.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] A simple communications protocol, such as Blink'n'Dim, delivers dimming commands via the power line.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] They enable computer control via networked switches, but do not require it.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Their cost is about the same as the older "dimmability" circuitry that they replace in LED bulbs, fixtures or drivers.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Early dimmers were directly controlled through the manual manipulation of large dimmer panels.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This required all power to come through the lighting control location, which could be inconvenient, inefficient and potentially dangerous for large or high-powered systems, such as those used for stage lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In 1896, Granville Woods patented his "safety dimmer", which greatly reduced wasted energy by reducing the amount of energy generated to match desired demand rather than burning off unwanted energy.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Spira, who later founded the Lutron Electronics Company in 1961, invented a dimmer based on a then-new solid state switching device called a silicon controlled rectifier or SCR.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This small device allowed the dimmer to be installed in a standard electrical wall box while saving energy.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In 1966, Eugene Alessio patented a light bulb socket adapter for adjusting the light level on a single light bulb using a TRIAC.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] To house this device, he decided on a 2-inch (51 mm) round device with one end capable of being screwed into a light bulb socket and the other end able to receive a light bulb.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] When solid-state dimmers came into use, analogue remote control systems (such as 0-10 V lighting control systems) became feasible.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The wire for the control systems was much smaller (with low current and lower danger) than the heavy power cables of previous lighting systems.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Each dimmer had its own control wires, resulting in many wires leaving the lighting control location.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] More recent digital control protocols such as DMX512, DALI, or one of the many Ethernet-based protocols like Art-Net, ETCnet, sACN, Pathport, ShowNet or KiNET enable the control of a large number of dimmers (and other stage equipment) through a single cable.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Dimmers based on rheostats were inefficient since they would dissipate a significant portion of the power rating of the load as heat.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] They were large and required plenty of cooling air.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Because their dimming effect depended a great deal on the total load applied to each rheostat, the load needed to be matched fairly carefully to the power rating of the rheostat.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Finally, as they relied on mechanical control they were slow and it was difficult to change many channels at a time.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Early examples of a rheostat dimmer include a salt water dimmer, a kind of liquid rheostat; the liquid between a movable and fixed contact provided a variable resistance.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The closer the contacts to each other, the more voltage was available for the light.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Salt water dimmers required regular addition of water and maintenance due to corrosion; exposed parts were energized during operation, presenting a shock hazard.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The coil-rotation transformer used a fixed-position electromagnet coil in conjunction with a variable-position coil to vary the voltage in the line by varying the alignment of the two coils.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Rotated 90 degrees apart, the secondary coil is affected by two equal but opposite fields from the primary, which effectively cancel each other out and produce no voltage in the secondary.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] These coils resembled the standard rotor and stator as used in an electric motor, except that the rotor was held against rotation using brakes and was moved to specific positions using high-torque gearing.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Because the rotor did not ever turn a complete revolution, a commutator was not required and long flexible cables could be used on the rotor instead.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Variable autotransformers (trade name "Variac") were then introduced.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] While they are still nearly as large as rheostat dimmers, which they closely resemble, they are relatively efficient devices.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Their voltage output, and so their dimming effect, is largely independent of the load applied so it was far easier to design the lighting that would be attached to each autotransformer channel.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Remote control of the dimmers was still impractical, although some dimmers were equipped with motor drives that could slowly and steadily reduce or increase the brightness of the attached lamps.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Autotransformers have fallen out of use for lighting but are used for other applications.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] However, there are certain lighting scenarios in which autotransformers are still a desirable solution (as of 2021).
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] For instance, the control room of an audio recording studio may require an extremely strict limit for electromagnetic interference.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In comparison with solid-state dimmers, the conducted emissions produced by autotransformers are effectively zero.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Solid-state, or semiconductor, dimmers were introduced to solve some of these problems.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Semiconductor dimmers switch on at an adjustable time (phase angle) after the start of each alternating-current half-cycle, thereby altering the voltage waveform applied to lamps and so changing its RMS effective value.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Because they switch instead of absorbing part of the voltage supplied, there is very little wasted power.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Dimming can be almost instantaneous and is easily controlled by remote electronics.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This development also made it possible to make dimmers small enough to be used in place (within the pattress) of normal domestic light switches.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The switches generate some heat during switching and can also cause radio-frequency interference.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Inductors or chokes are used as part of the circuitry to suppress this interference.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The suppression circuitry might be insufficient to prevent buzzing to be heard on sensitive audio and radio equipment that shares the mains supply with the lighting loads.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In this case, special steps must be taken to prevent this interference.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] European dimmers must comply with relevant EMC legislation requirements; this involves suppressing the emissions described above to limits described in EN55104.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In the electrical schematic shown, a typical light dimmer based on a silicon-controlled rectifier (SCR) dims the light through phase-angle control.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This unit is wired in series with the load.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Diodes (D2, D3, D4 and D5) form a bridge, which generates pulsed DC.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] R1 and C1 form a circuit with a time constant.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] As the voltage increases from zero (at the start of every halfwave) C1 charges up.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] When C1 is able to make Zener diode D6 conduct and inject current into the SCR, the SCR fires.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] When the SCR conducts, D1 discharges C1 through the SCR.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The SCR shuts off when the current falls to zero and the supply voltage drops at the end of the half cycle, ready for the circuit to start work on the next half cycle.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This circuit is called a **leading-edge dimmer** or **forward phase dimming**.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Dimmers based on insulated-gate bipolar transistors (IGBTs) do away with most of the noise present in TRIACs by chopping off the falling side of the sine wave.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] These circuits are called **trailing-edge dimmers** or **reverse phase dimming**.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] An even newer, but still expensive technology is **sine-wave dimming**, which is implemented as a high-power switched-mode power supply followed by a filter.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Multi-Volt or mVolt lamps can operate seamlessly at multiple voltages, typically ranging from 120 Volts to 277 Volts.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Multi-Volt lamps produce the same amount of light regardless of supply Voltage.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Dimming is accomplished by a separate 0-10 V lighting control dimming signal.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Non domestic dimmers are usually controlled remotely by means of various protocols.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Analogue dimmers usually require a separate wire for each channel of dimming carrying a voltage between 0 and 10 V.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Some analogue circuitry then derives a control signal from this and the mains supply for the switches.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] As more channels are added to the system more wires are needed between the lighting controller and the dimmers.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In the late 1970s, serial analogue protocols were developed.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] These multiplexed a series of analogue levels onto a single wire, with embedded clocking signal similar to a composite video signal (in the case of Strand Lighting's European D54 standard, handling 384 dimmers) or separate clocking signal (in the case of the US standard AMX192).
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Digital protocols, such as DMX512 have proved to be the answer since the late 1980s.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In early implementations a digital signal was sent from the controller to a **demultiplexer**, which sat next to the dimmers.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This converted the digital signal into a collection of 0 to +10 V or 0 to −10 V signals which could be connected to the individual analogue control circuits.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Modern dimmer designs use microprocessors to convert the digital signal directly into a control signal for the switches.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This has many advantages, giving closer control over the dimming, and giving the opportunity for diagnostic feedback to be sent digitally back to the lighting controller.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Some dimmers in residential applications are also equipped with a radio receiver to be used as wireless light switches which can be remotely controlled by a radio transmitter.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Patching is the physical ("hard patch") or virtual ("soft patch") assignment to a circuit or channel for the purpose of control.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Dimmers are usually arranged together in racks, where they can be accessed easily, and then power is run to the instruments being controlled.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In architectural installations electricity is run straight from the dimmers to the lights via permanent wiring (this is called a **circuit**).
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] They are hard run and cannot be changed.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] However venues such as theatres demand more flexibility.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] To allow for changes for each show, and occasionally during shows, theatres sometimes install circuits run permanently to sockets around the theatre.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Instead of these circuits going directly to the dimmer they are connected to a *patch bay*.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] A patch bay usually sits next to the dimmers enabling the dimmers to be connected to specific circuits via a patch cable.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The patch bay may also enable many circuits to be connected to one dimmer and even series connection for low-voltage lamps.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Also in some theatres individual cables are run directly from the light to dimmer.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The assigned connections between the circuits (either at the patch bay or in the form of individual cables) and the dimmers is known as the **mains** or **hard patch**.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This is most common in older theatres, and on a tour where dimmers will be brought in by the touring company.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Most modern fixed installations do not have patch bays; instead they have a dimmer-per-circuit, and patch dimmers into channels using a computerized control console's **Soft Patch**.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The design of most analogue dimmers meant that the output of the dimmer was not directly proportional to the input.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Instead, as the operator brought up a fader, the dimmer would dim slowly at first, then quickly in the middle, then slowly at the top.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The shape of the curve resembled that of the third quarter of a sine wave.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Different dimmers produced different dimmer curves, and different applications typically demanded different responses.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Television often uses a "square law" curve, providing finer control in top part of the curve, essential to allow accurate trimming of the colour temperature of lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Theatrical dimmers tend to use a softer "S" or linear curve.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Digital dimmers can be made to have whatever curve the manufacturer desires; they may have a choice between a linear relationship and selection of different curves, so that they can be matched with older analogue dimmers.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Sophisticated systems provide user-programmable or nonstandard curves, and a common use of a nonstandard curve is to turn a dimmer into a "non-dim", switching on at a user defined control level.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Switching high-intensity incandescent (filament) lamps to full power from cold can shorten their life dramatically, owing to the large inrush current that occurs.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] To reduce stress on the lamp filaments, dimmers may have a **preheat** function.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This sets a minimum level, usually between 5% and 10%, which appears turned-off, but stops the lamp from cooling down too much.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This also speeds up the lamp's reaction to sudden bursts of power that operators of rock'n'roll-style shows appreciate.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The opposite of this function is sometimes called **top-set**.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This limits the maximum power supplied to a lamp, which can also extend its life.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In less advanced systems, this same effect is achieved by literally pre-heating (warming) the globes before an event or performance.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This is usually achieved by slowly bringing the lights up to full (or usually 90-95%) power over a period of between 1/2 to 1 hour.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This is as effective as a built-in preheat function.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Modern digital desks can emulate preheat and dimmer curves and allow a soft patch to be done in memory.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] This is often preferred as it means that the dimmer rack can be exchanged for another one without having to transfer complicated settings.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Many different curves, or *profiles* can be programmed and used on different channels.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] One measure of the quality of a leading edge dimmer is the "rise time".
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] The rise time in this context is the amount of time it takes for the cut part of the waveform to get from zero to the instantaneous output voltage.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] In the waveform above it is a measure of the slope of the almost vertical edge of the red trace.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Typically it is measured in tens to hundreds of microseconds.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] A longer rise time reduces the noise of the dimmer and the lamp as well as extending the life of the lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] A longer rise time also reduces the electromagnetic interference produced by the dimmer.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Unsurprisingly, a longer rise time is more expensive to implement than a short one, this is because the size of choke has to be increased.
[src:dali-lighting/dimmer] Newer dimming methods can help minimize such problems.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] An **electrical ballast** is a device placed in series with a load to limit the amount of current in an electrical circuit.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A familiar and widely used example is the inductive ballast used in fluorescent lamps to limit the current through the tube, which would otherwise rise to a destructive level due to the negative differential resistance of the tube's voltage-current characteristic.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] They may be as simple as a resistor, inductor, or capacitor (or a combination of these) wired in series with the lamp; or as complex as the electronic ballasts used in compact fluorescent lamps (CFLs).
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] An electrical ballast is a device that limits the current through an electrical load.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] These are most often used when a load (such as an arc discharge) has its terminal voltage decline when current through the load increases.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] If such a device were connected to a constant-voltage power supply, it would draw an increasing amount of current until it is destroyed or causes the power supply to fail.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] To prevent this, a ballast provides a positive resistance or reactance that limits the current available to that device.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Ballasts can also be used simply to limit the current in an ordinary, positive-resistance circuit.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Prior to the advent of solid-state ignition, automobile ignition systems commonly included a ballast resistor to regulate the voltage applied to the ignition system.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] For simple, low-powered loads such as a neon lamp, a fixed resistor is commonly used.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Because the resistance of the ballast resistor is large, it determines the current in the circuit, even in the face of negative resistance introduced by the neon lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A ballast resistor was also used in early models automobile engines to lower the supply voltage to the ignition system after the engine had been started.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Starting the engine requires a significant amount of electrical current from the battery, resulting in an equally significant voltage drop.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] To allow the engine to start, the ignition system was designed to operate on this lower voltage.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] But once the vehicle was started and the starter disengaged, the battery's normal operating voltage was too high for the ignition system.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] To avoid this problem, a ballast resistor was inserted in series with the ignition system, resulting in two different operating voltages for the starting and ignition systems.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Occasionally, this ballast resistor would fail and the classic symptom of this failure was that the engine ran while being cranked (while the resistor was bypassed) but stalled immediately when cranking ceased (and the resistor was reconnected in the circuit via the ignition switch).
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Modern electronic ignition systems (those used since the 1980s or late 1970s) do not require a ballast resistor as they are flexible enough to operate on the lower cranking voltage or the normal operating voltage.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Another common use of a ballast resistor in the automotive industry is adjusting the ventilation fan speed.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The ballast is a fixed resistor with usually two center taps, and the fan speed selector switch is used to bypass portions of the ballast: all of them for full speed, and none for the low speed setting.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A very common failure occurs when the fan is being constantly run at the next-to-full speed setting (usually 3 out of 4).
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] This will cause a very short piece of resistor coil to be operated with a relatively high current (up to 10 A), eventually burning it out.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] This will render the fan unable to run at the reduced speed settings.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] In some consumer electronic equipment, notably in television sets in the era of valves (vacuum tubes), but also in some low-cost record players, the vacuum tube heaters were connected in series.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Since the voltage drop across all the heaters in series was usually less than the full mains voltage, it was necessary to provide a ballast to drop the excess voltage.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A resistor was often used for this purpose, as it was cheap and worked with both alternating current (AC) and direct current (DC).
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Some ballast resistors have the property of increasing in resistance as current through them increases, and decreasing in resistance as current decreases.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Physically, some such devices are often built quite like incandescent lamps.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Like the tungsten filament of an ordinary incandescent lamp, if current increases, the ballast resistor gets hotter, its resistance goes up, and its voltage drop increases.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] If current decreases, the ballast resistor gets colder, its resistance drops, and the voltage drop decreases.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Therefore, the ballast resistor reduces variations in current, despite variations in applied voltage or changes in the rest of an electric circuit.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] These devices are sometimes called "barretters" and were used in the series heating circuits of 1930s to 1960s AC/DC radio and TV home receivers.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] This property can lead to more precise current control than merely choosing an appropriate fixed resistor.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The power lost in the resistive ballast is also reduced because a smaller portion of the overall power is dropped in the ballast compared to what might be required with a fixed resistor.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Household clothes dryers sometimes incorporated a germicidal lamp in series with an ordinary incandescent lamp; the incandescent lamp operated as the ballast for the germicidal lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A commonly used light in the home in the 1960s in 220–240 V countries was a circular tube ballasted by an under-run regular mains filament lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Self-ballasted mercury-vapor lamps incorporate ordinary tungsten filaments within the overall envelope of the lamp to act as the ballast, and to partially compensate for the red-deficient light produced by the mercury vapor process.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] An inductor, usually a choke, is very common in line-frequency ballasts to provide the proper starting and operating electrical condition to power a fluorescent lamp or a high intensity discharge lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The voltage spike produced when current through the inductor is rapidly interrupted is used in some circuits to first strike the arc in the lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A disadvantage of the inductor is that current is shifted out of phase with the voltage, producing a poor power factor.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] In more expensive ballasts, a capacitor is often paired with the inductor to correct the power factor.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] In autotransformer ballasts that control two or more lamps, line-frequency ballasts commonly use different phase relationships between the multiple lamps.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] This not only mitigates the flicker of the individual lamps, it also helps maintain a high power factor.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] These ballasts are often called *lead-lag* ballasts because the current in one lamp leads the mains phase and the current in the other lamp lags the mains phase.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] In most 220-240V ballasts, the capacitor isn't incorporated inside the ballast like in North American ballasts, but is wired in parallel or in series with the ballast.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] In Europe, and most 220-240 V territories, the line voltage is sufficient to start lamps over 30W with a series inductor.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] In North America and Japan, however, the line voltage (120 V or 100 V respectively) may not be sufficient to start lamps over 30 W with a series inductor, so an autotransformer winding is included in the ballast to step up the voltage.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The autotransformer is designed with enough leakage inductance (short-circuit inductance) so that the current is appropriately limited.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Because of the large inductors and capacitors that must be used, as well as the heavy iron core of the inductor, reactive ballasts operated at line frequency tend to be large and heavy.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] They commonly also produce acoustic noise (line-frequency hum).
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Prior to 1980 in the United States, polychlorinated biphenyl (PCB)-based oils were used as an insulating oil in many ballasts to provide cooling and electrical isolation (see Transformer oil).
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] An electronic ballast uses solid state electronic circuitry to provide the proper starting and operating electrical conditions to power discharge lamps.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] An electronic ballast can be smaller and lighter than a comparably rated magnetic one.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] An electronic ballast is usually quieter than a magnetic one, which produces a line-frequency hum by vibration of the core laminations.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Electronic ballasts are often based on switched-mode power supply (SMPS) topology, first rectifying the input power and then chopping it at a high frequency.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Advanced electronic ballasts may allow dimming via pulse-width modulation or via changing the frequency to a higher value.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Ballasts incorporating a microcontroller (digital ballasts) may offer remote control and monitoring via networks such as LonWorks, Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI), DMX512, Digital Serial Interface (DSI) or simple analog control using a 0-10 V DC brightness control signal.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Systems with remote control of light level via a wireless mesh network have been introduced.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The high output frequency of an electronic ballast refreshes the phosphors in a fluorescent lamp so rapidly that there is no perceptible flicker.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The flicker index, used for measuring perceptible light modulation, has a range from 0.00 to 1.00, with 0 indicating the lowest possibility of flickering and 1 indicating the highest.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Lamps operated on magnetic ballasts have a flicker index between 0.04 and 0.07, while digital ballasts have a flicker index of below 0.01.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Because more gas remains ionized in the arc stream, the lamp operates at about 9% higher efficacy above approximately 10 kHz.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Lamp efficiency increases sharply at about 10 kHz and continues to improve until approximately 20 kHz.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Electronic ballast retrofits to existing street lights had been tested in some Canadian provinces circa 2012; since then LED retrofits have become more common.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Low-pressure lamps, including fluorescent ones, are more efficient when driven by electronic ballasts.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] High-pressure lamps, like metal halide and high pressure sodium lamps, do not benefit from the use of electronic ballasts, as the higher switching frequency reduces these lamps' reliability due to acoustic resonance.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] These lamps are instead efficient when driven with low frequency square wave current, in the range of 100 – 400 Hz.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Many modern electronic ballasts can operate both high pressure sodium (HPS) lamps as well as metal-halide lamps.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The ballast initially works as a starter for the arc by its internal ignitor, supplying a high-voltage impulse and, later, it works as a limiter/regulator of the electric flow inside the circuit.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Electronic ballasts also run much cooler and are lighter than their magnetic counterparts.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] This technique uses a combination filament–cathode at each end of the lamp in conjunction with a mechanical or automatic (bi-metallic or electronic) switch that initially connects the filaments in series with the ballast to preheat them.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] When filaments are disconnected, an inductive pulse from the ballast starts the lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] This system is described as "Preheat" in North America and "Switch Start" in the UK, and has no specific description in the rest of the world.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] This system is common in 200–240 V countries (and for 100–120 V lamps up to about 30 watts).
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Although an inductive pulse makes it more likely that the lamp will start when the starter switch opens, it is not actually necessary.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The ballast in such systems can equally be a resistor.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A number of fluorescent lamp fittings used a filament lamp as the ballast in the late 1950s through to the 1960s.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Special lamps were manufactured that were rated at 170 volts and 120 watts.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The lamp had a thermal starter built into the 4-pin base.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The power requirements were much larger than using an inductive ballast (though the consumed current was the same), but the warmer light from the lamp-type ballast was often preferred by users, particularly in a domestic environment.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Resistive ballasts were used with direct current (DC) supplies.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] These fittings used the thermal type of starter, and may also have included a choke in the circuit to provide a pulse on opening of the starter switchfor imporved starting.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] DC fittings were complicated by the need to reverse the polarity of the supply to the tube each time it started.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Failure to do so vastly shortened the life of the tube.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] An instant start ballast does not preheat the electrodes, instead using a relatively high voltage (~600 V) to initiate the discharge arc.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] It is the most energy-efficient type, but yields the fewest lamp-start cycles, as material is blasted from the surface of the cold electrodes each time the lamp is turned on.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Instant-start ballasts are best suited to applications with long duty cycles, where the lamps are not frequently turned on and off.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Although these were mostly used in countries with 100-120 volt mains supplies (for lamps of 40 W or above), they were briefly popular in other countries because the lamp started without the flicker of switch start systems.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The popularity was short lived because of the short lamp life.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A rapid start ballast heats the lamp electrodes continually during operation, using a heating supply winding on the transformer ballast.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Rapid start provides longer lamp life and more cycle life than instant start, but has very high ballast losses due to the heating power supplied to the electrodes.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Although popular in the United States and Canada for lamps of 40 W and above, rapid start is sometimes used in other countries, particularly where the flicker of switch start systems is undesirable.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A dimmable ballast is very similar to a rapid start ballast, except that the ballasting coil is connected to a dimmer.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A quadrac type light dimmer can be used with a dimming ballast, which maintains the heating current while allowing lamp current to be controlled.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A resistor of about 10 kΩ is required to be connected in parallel with the fluorescent tube to allow reliable firing of the quadrac at low light levels.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] There are dimmable electronic ballast that uses 1-10V or DALI interfaces to dim the lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] An electronic ballast with an integrated rechargeable battery is designed to provide emergency egress lighting in the event of a power failure.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] It can be incorporated into an existing fluorescent light fixture or mounted remotely outside of it.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] When power is lost, the ballast will illuminate one or more lamps in the fixture at a reduced output for a minimum of 90 minutes (as required by code).
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] These can be used as an alternative to egress lighting powered by a back-up electrical generator.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] A hybrid ballast is a magnetic ballast with an integrated electronic starter.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Like a magnetic ballast, a hybrid unit operates at line power frequency—50 Hz in Europe, for example.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] These types of ballasts, which are also referred to as *cathode-disconnect ballasts*, disconnect the electrode-heating circuit after they start the lamps.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] For a lighting ballast, the ANSI ballast factor is used in North America to compare the light output (in lumens) of a lamp operated on a ballast compared to the lamp operating on an ANSI reference ballast.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Reference ballast operates the lamp at its ANSI-specified nominal power rating.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] The ballast factor of practical ballasts must be considered in lighting design; a low ballast factor may save energy, but will produce less light and short the lamp life.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] With fluorescent lamps, ballast factor can vary from the reference value of 1.0.
[src:dali-lighting/electrical-ballast] Early tube-based color TV sets used a ballast triode, such as the PD500, as a parallel shunt stabilizer for the cathode-ray tube (CRT) acceleration voltage, to keep the CRT's deflection factor constant.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] A **light-emitting diode** (**LED**) is an electronic component that uses a semiconductor to emit light when current flows through it.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Electrons in the semiconductor recombine with electron holes, thereby releasing energy in the form of photons.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The color of the light (corresponding to the energy of the photons) is determined by the energy required for electrons to cross the band gap of the semiconductor.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] White light is obtained by using multiple semiconductors or a layer of light-emitting phosphor on the semiconductor device.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Appearing as practical electronic components in 1962, the earliest LEDs emitted low-intensity infrared (IR) light.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Infrared LEDs are used in remote-control circuits, such as those used with a wide variety of consumer electronics.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The first visible-light LEDs were of low intensity and limited to red.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Early LEDs were often used as indicator lamps, replacing small incandescent bulbs, and in seven-segment displays.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Later developments produced LEDs available in visible, ultraviolet (UV), and infrared wavelengths with high, low, or intermediate light output; for instance, white LEDs suitable for room and outdoor lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LEDs have also given rise to new types of displays and sensors, while their high switching rates have uses in advanced communications technology.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LEDs have been used in diverse applications such as aviation lighting, fairy lights, strip lights, automotive headlamps, advertising, stage lighting, general lighting, traffic signals, camera flashes, lighted wallpaper, horticultural grow lights, and medical devices.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LEDs have many advantages over incandescent light sources, including lower power consumption, reduced waste heat, a longer lifetime, improved physical robustness, smaller sizes, and faster switching.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LEDs are transducers of electricity into light.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Electroluminescence from a solid state diode was discovered in 1906 by Henry Joseph Round of Marconi Labs, and was published in February 1907 in Electrical World.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Round observed that various carborundum (silicon carbide) crystals would emit yellow, light green, orange, or blue light when a voltage was passed between the poles.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] A silicon carbide LED was created by Soviet inventor Oleg Losev in 1927.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Commercially viable LEDs only became available after Texas Instruments engineers patented efficient near-infrared emission from a diode based on GaAs in 1962.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Commercial LEDs were extremely costly and saw no practical use until Monsanto and Hewlett-Packard developed them to the point where a unit cost less than five cents in the 1970s.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] In the early 1990s, Shuji Nakamura, Hiroshi Amano and Isamu Akasaki developed blue light-emitting diodes, bringing white lighting and full-color LED displays into practical use.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] For this work, they won the 2014 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] In a light-emitting diode, the recombination of electrons and electron holes in a semiconductor produces light (infrared, visible or UV), a process called electroluminescence.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The wavelength of the light depends on the energy band gap of the semiconductors used.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Since these materials have a high index of refraction, design features of the devices, such as special optical coatings and die shape, are required to efficiently emit light.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Unlike a laser, the light emitted from an LED is neither spectrally nor spatially coherent nor even highly monochromatic.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Its spectrum is sufficiently narrow that it appears to the human eye as a pure (saturated) color.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Also, it cannot approach the very high intensity characteristic of lasers.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] By selection of different semiconductor materials, single-color LEDs can be made that emit light in a narrow band of wavelengths, from the near-infrared through the visible spectrum and into the ultraviolet range.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The required operating voltages of LEDs increase as the emitted wavelengths become shorter (higher energy, red to blue), because of their increasing semiconductor band gap.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Blue LEDs have an active region consisting of one or more InGaN quantum wells sandwiched between thicker layers of GaN, called cladding layers.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] By varying the relative In/Ga fraction in the InGaN quantum wells, the light emission can in theory be varied from violet to amber.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Aluminium gallium nitride (AlGaN) of varying Al/Ga fraction can be used to manufacture the cladding and quantum well layers for ultraviolet LEDs, but these devices have not yet reached the level of efficiency and technological maturity of InGaN/GaN blue/green devices.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] If unalloyed GaN is used in this case to form the active quantum well layers, the device emits near-ultraviolet light with a peak wavelength centered around 365 nm.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Green LEDs manufactured from the InGaN/GaN system are far more efficient and brighter than green LEDs produced with non-nitride material systems, but practical devices still exhibit efficiency too low for high-brightness applications.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] With AlGaN and AlGaInN, even shorter wavelengths are achievable.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Near-UV emitters at wavelengths around 360–395 nm are already cheap and often encountered, for example, as black light lamp replacements for inspection of anti-counterfeiting UV watermarks in documents and bank notes, and for UV curing.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Substantially more expensive, shorter-wavelength diodes are commercially available for wavelengths down to 240 nm.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] As the photosensitivity of microorganisms approximately matches the absorption spectrum of DNA, with a peak at about 260 nm, UV LED emitting at 250–270 nm are expected in prospective disinfection and sterilization devices.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Recent research has shown that commercially available UVA LEDs (365 nm) are already effective disinfection and sterilization devices.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] UV-C wavelengths were obtained in laboratories using aluminium nitride (210 nm), boron nitride (215 nm) and diamond (235 nm).
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] There are two primary ways of producing white light-emitting diodes (**WLED**).
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] One is to use individual LEDs that emit three primary colors—red, green and blue—and then mix all the colors to form white light.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The other, more common method is to use a phosphor material to convert monochromatic light from a blue or UV LED to broad-spectrum white light, similar to a fluorescent lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The yellow phosphor is made of cerium-doped YAG crystals suspended in the package or coated on the LED.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] This YAG phosphor causes white LEDs to appear yellow when off, and the spaces between the crystals allow some blue light to pass through in LEDs with partial phosphor conversion.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Alternatively, white LEDs may use other phosphors like manganese(IV)-doped potassium fluorosilicate (PFS) or other engineered phosphors.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] PFS assists in red light generation, and is used in conjunction with a conventional Ce:YAG phosphor.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] In LEDs with PFS phosphor, some blue light passes through the phosphors, the Ce:YAG phosphor converts blue light to green and red (yellow) light, and the PFS phosphor converts blue light to red light.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The color emission spectrum or color temperature of white phosphor-converted and other phosphor-converted LEDs can be controlled by changing the concentration of several phosphors that form a phosphor blend used in an LED package.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The 'whiteness' of the light produced is engineered to suit the human eye.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Because of metamerism, it is possible to have quite different spectra that appear white.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The appearance of objects illuminated by that light may vary as the spectrum varies.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] This is the issue of color rendition, quite separate from color temperature.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] An orange or cyan object could appear with the wrong color and much darker as the LED or phosphor does not emit the wavelength it reflects.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The best color rendition LEDs use a mix of phosphors, resulting in less efficiency and better color rendering.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The first white light-emitting diodes (LEDs) were offered for sale in the autumn of 1996.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Nichia made some of the first white LEDs which were based on blue LEDs with Ce:YAG phosphor.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Ce:YAG is often grown using the Czochralski method.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Mixing red, green, and blue sources to produce white light needs electronic circuits to control the blending of the colors.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Since LEDs have slightly different emission patterns, the color balance may change depending on the angle of view, even if the RGB sources are in a single package, so RGB diodes are seldom used to produce white lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Nonetheless, this method has many applications because of the flexibility of mixing different colors, and in principle, this mechanism also has higher quantum efficiency in producing white light.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] There are several types of multicolor white LEDs: di-, tri-, and tetrachromatic white LEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Several key factors that play among these different methods include color stability, color rendering capability, and luminous efficacy.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Often, higher efficiency means lower color rendering, presenting a trade-off between the luminous efficacy and color rendering.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] For example, the dichromatic white LEDs have the best luminous efficacy (120 lm/W), but the lowest color rendering capability.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Although tetrachromatic white LEDs have excellent color rendering capability, they often have poor luminous efficacy.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Trichromatic white LEDs are in between, having both good luminous efficacy (>70 lm/W) and fair color rendering capability.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] One of the challenges is the development of more efficient green LEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The theoretical maximum for green LEDs is 683 lumens per watt, but as of 2010 few green LEDs exceed even 100 lumens per watt.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The blue and red LEDs approach their theoretical limits.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Multicolor LEDs offer a means to form light of different colors.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Most perceivable colors can be formed by mixing different amounts of three primary colors.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] This allows precise dynamic color control.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Their emission power decays exponentially with rising temperature, resulting in a substantial change in color stability.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Multicolor LEDs without phosphors cannot provide good color rendering because each LED is a narrowband source.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LEDs without phosphors, while a poorer solution for general lighting, are the best solution for displays, whether they are LCD-backlit or direct LED-based pixels.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Dimming a multicolor LED source to match the characteristics of incandescent lamps is difficult because manufacturing variations, age, and temperature change the actual color value output.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] To emulate the appearance of dimming in incandescent lamps, LEDs may require a feedback system with color sensor to actively monitor and control the color.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] This method involves coating LEDs of one color (mostly blue LEDs made of InGaN) with phosphors of different colors to form white light; the resultant LEDs are called phosphor-based or phosphor-converted white LEDs (pcLEDs).
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] A fraction of the blue light undergoes the Stokes shift, which transforms it from shorter wavelengths to longer.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Depending on the original LED's color, various color phosphors are used.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Using several phosphor layers of distinct colors broadens the emitted spectrum, effectively raising the color rendering index (CRI).
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Phosphor-based LEDs have efficiency losses due to heat loss from the Stokes shift and other phosphor-related issues.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Their luminous efficacies compared to normal LEDs depend on the spectral distribution of the resultant light output and the original wavelength of the LED itself.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] For example, the luminous efficacy of a typical YAG yellow phosphor based white LED ranges from 3 to 5 times the luminous efficacy of the original blue LED because of the human eye's greater sensitivity to yellow than to blue (as modeled in the luminosity function).
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Due to the simplicity of manufacturing, the phosphor method is still the most popular method for making high-intensity white LEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The design and production of a light source or light fixture using a monochrome emitter with phosphor conversion is simpler and cheaper than a complex RGB system, and the majority of high-intensity white LEDs presently on the market are manufactured using phosphor light conversion.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Among the challenges being faced to improve the efficiency of LED-based white light sources is the development of more efficient phosphors.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] As of 2010, the most efficient yellow phosphor is still the YAG phosphor, with less than 10% Stokes shift loss.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Losses attributable to internal optical losses due to re-absorption in the LED chip and in the LED packaging itself typically account for another 10% to 30% loss.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Currently, in the area of phosphor LED development, much effort is being spent on optimizing these devices to higher light output and higher operation temperatures.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] For instance, the efficiency can be raised by adapting better package design or by using a more suitable type of phosphor.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Conformal coating process is frequently used to address the issue of varying phosphor thickness.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Some phosphor-based white LEDs encapsulate InGaN blue LEDs inside phosphor-coated epoxy.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Alternatively, the LED might be paired with a remote phosphor, a preformed polycarbonate piece coated with the phosphor material.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Remote phosphors provide more diffuse light, which is desirable for many applications.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Remote phosphor designs are also more tolerant of variations in the LED emissions spectrum.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] A common yellow phosphor material is cerium-doped yttrium aluminium garnet (Ce3+:YAG).
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] White LEDs can also be made by coating near-ultraviolet (NUV) LEDs with a mixture of high-efficiency europium-based phosphors that emit red and blue, plus copper and aluminium-doped zinc sulfide (ZnS:Cu, Al) that emits green.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] This is a method analogous to the way fluorescent lamps work.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] This method is less efficient than blue LEDs with YAG:Ce phosphor, as the Stokes shift is larger, but it yields light with better spectral characteristics, which render color better.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Due to the higher radiative output of the ultraviolet LEDs than of the blue ones, both methods offer comparable brightness.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] A concern is that UV light may leak from a malfunctioning light source and cause harm to human eyes or skin.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] A new style of wafers composed of gallium-nitride-on-silicon (GaN-on-Si) is being used to produce white LEDs using 200-mm silicon wafers.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] This avoids the typical costly sapphire substrate for relatively small 100- or 150-mm wafer sizes.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The sapphire apparatus must be coupled with a mirror-like collector to reflect light that would otherwise be wasted.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] It was predicted that in 2020, 40% of all GaN LEDs are made with GaN-on-Si.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] There are RGBW LEDs that combine RGB units with a phosphor white LED on the market.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Doing so retains the extremely tunable color of RGB LEDs, but allows color rendering and efficiency to be optimized when a color close to white is selected.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Some phosphor white LED units are "tunable white", blending two extremes of color temperatures (commonly 2700K and 6500K) to produce intermediate values.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] This feature allows users to change the lighting to suit the current use of a multifunction room.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] As illustrated by a straight line on the chromaticity diagram, simple two-white blends will have a pink bias, becoming most severe in the middle.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] A small amount of green light, provided by another LED, could correct the problem.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] A final class of white LED with mixed light is dim-to-warm.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] These are ordinary 2700K white LED bulbs with a small red LED that turns on when the bulb is dimmed.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Doing so makes the color warmer, emulating an incandescent light bulb.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Experimental white LEDs have been developed using homoepitaxially grown zinc selenide (ZnSe) on ZnSe substrates.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] These LEDs lack the yellow phosphors found in conventional white LEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] In ZnSe LEDs, the active region emits blue light, while the conductive ZnSe substrate emits yellow light, resulting in white light output.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Researchers suggest these LEDs offer lower operating voltages and a wider range of color temperatures than conventional white LEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] In an organic light-emitting diode (OLED), the electroluminescent material composing the emissive layer of the diode is an organic compound.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The organic material is electrically conductive due to the delocalization of pi electrons caused by conjugation over all or part of the molecule, and the material therefore functions as an organic semiconductor.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The organic materials can be small organic molecules in a crystalline phase, or polymers.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The potential advantages of OLEDs include thin, low-cost displays with a low driving voltage, wide viewing angle, and high contrast and color gamut.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Polymer LEDs have the added benefit of printable and flexible displays.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] OLEDs have been used to make visual displays for portable electronic devices such as cellphones, digital cameras, lighting and televisions.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LEDs are made in different packages for different applications.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] A single or a few LED junctions may be packed in one miniature device for use as an indicator or pilot lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] An LED array may include controlling circuits within the same package, which may range from a simple resistor, blinking or color changing control, or an addressable controller for RGB devices.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Higher-powered white-emitting devices will be mounted on heat sinks and will be used for illumination.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Alphanumeric displays in dot matrix or bar formats are widely available.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Special packages permit connection of LEDs to optical fibers for high-speed data communication links.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] These are mostly single-die LEDs used as indicators, and they come in various sizes from 1.8 mm to 10 mm, through-hole and surface mount packages.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Typical current ratings range from around 1 mA to above 20 mA.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LED's can be soldered to a flexible PCB strip to form LED tape popularly used for decoration.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Common package shapes include round, with a domed or flat top, rectangular with a flat top (as used in bar-graph displays), and triangular or square with a flat top.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The encapsulation may also be clear or tinted to improve contrast and viewing angle.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Infrared devices may have a black tint to block visible light while passing infrared radiation, such as the Osram SFH 4546.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] 5 V and 12 V LEDs are ordinary miniature LEDs that have a series resistor for direct connection to a 5 V or 12 V supply.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] High-power LEDs (HP-LEDs) or high-output LEDs (HO-LEDs) can be driven at currents from hundreds of mA to more than an ampere, compared with the tens of mA for other LEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LED power densities up to 300 W/cm2 have been achieved.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Since overheating is destructive, the HP-LEDs must be mounted on a heat sink to allow for heat dissipation.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] If the heat from an HP-LED is not removed, the device fails in seconds.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] One HP-LED can often replace an incandescent bulb in a flashlight, or be set in an array to form a powerful LED lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Some HP-LEDs in this category are the Nichia 19 series, Lumileds Rebel Led, Osram Opto Semiconductors Golden Dragon, and Cree X-lamp.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] As of September 2009, some HP-LEDs manufactured by Cree exceed 105 lm/W.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Examples for Haitz's law—which predicts an exponential rise in light output and efficacy of LEDs over time—are the CREE XP-G series LED, which achieved 105 lm/W in 2009 and the Nichia 19 series with a typical efficacy of 140 lm/W, released in 2010.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LEDs developed by Seoul Semiconductor can operate on AC power without a DC converter.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] For each half-cycle, part of the LED emits light and part is dark, and this is reversed during the next half-cycle.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The efficiency of this type of HP-LED is typically 40 lm/W.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] A large number of LED elements in series may be able to operate directly from line voltage.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] In 2009, Seoul Semiconductor released a high DC voltage LED, named 'Acrich MJT', capable of being driven from AC power with a simple controlling circuit.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The low-power dissipation of these LEDs affords them more flexibility than the original AC LED design.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] An LED strip light is a flexible circuit board populated by surface-mount LEDs and other components that usually comes with an adhesive backing.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LED lamps have been widely adopted in personal, professional, and hobbyist environments for their aesthetic, functionality, and flexibility.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Traditionally, strip lights had been used solely in accent lighting, backlighting, task lighting, and decorative lighting applications, such as cove lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LED strip lights were first produced in the early 2000s.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] There are many types of LED Strips each with different codenames and LED types.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Each one can vary in input power, led spacing, color capability and more.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Flashing LEDs are used as attention seeking indicators without requiring external electronics.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] circuit that causes the LED to flash with a typical period of one second.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] In diffused lens LEDs, this circuit is visible as a small black dot.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Most flashing LEDs emit light of one color, but more sophisticated devices can flash between multiple colors and even fade through a color sequence using RGB color mixing.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Flashing SMD LEDs in the 0805 and other size formats have been available since early 2019.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Sometimes a flickering effect might happen due to an electric malfunction.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Bi-color LEDs contain two different LED emitters in one case.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Current flow in one direction emits one color, and current in the opposite direction emits the other color.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The other type consists of two dies with separate leads for both dies and another lead for common anode or cathode so that they can be controlled independently.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Others include amber/traditional green, red/pure green, red/blue, and blue/pure green.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Tri-color LEDs contain three different LED emitters in one case.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Each emitter is connected to a separate lead so they can be controlled independently.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] A four-lead arrangement is typical with one common lead (anode or cathode) and an additional lead for each color.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Others have only two leads (positive and negative) and have a built-in electronic controller.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LEDs consist of one red, one green, and one blue LED.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] each of the three, RGB LEDs are capable of producing a wide color gamut.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Unlike dedicated-color LEDs, these do not produce pure wavelengths.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Modules may not be optimized for smooth color mixing.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Decorative-multicolor LEDs incorporate several emitters of different colors supplied by only two lead-out wires.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Colors are switched internally by varying the supply voltage.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Seven-segment displays handle all numbers and a limited set of letters.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Starburst displays can display all letters.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Dot-matrix displays typically use 5×7 pixels per character.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] , with their lower power needs and greater display flexibility, has reduced the popularity of numeric and alphanumeric LED displays.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Digital RGB addressable LEDs contain their own "smart" control electronics.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] In addition to power and ground, these provide connections for data-in, data-out, clock and sometimes a strobe signal.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] to be easily controlled by a microcontroller.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Data sent to the first LED of the chain can control the brightness and color of each LED independently of the others.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] They are used where a combination of maximum control and minimum visible electronics are needed such as strings for Christmas and LED matrices.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Some even have refresh rates in the kHz range, allowing for basic video applications.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] consists of multiple LED chips connected in series on a common longitudinal substrate that forms a thin rod reminiscent of a traditional incandescent filament.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] These are being used as a low-cost decorative alternative for traditional light bulbs that are being phased out in many countries.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The filaments use a rather high voltage, allowing them to work efficiently with mains voltages.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Often a simple rectifier and capacitive current limiting are employed to create a low-cost replacement for a traditional light bulb without the complexity of the low voltage, high current converter that single die LEDs need.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Usually, they are packaged in bulb similar to the lamps they were designed to replace, and filled with inert gas at slightly lower than ambient pressure to remove heat efficiently and prevent corrosion.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] (COB) arrays, allowing better heat dissipation than with a single LED of comparable luminous output.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The LEDs can be arranged around a cylinder, and are called "corn cob lights" because of the rows of yellow LEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The current in an LED or other diodes rises exponentially with the applied voltage (see Shockley diode equation), so a small change in voltage can cause a large change in current.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Current through the LED must be regulated by an external circuit such as a constant current source to prevent damage.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] They must be supplied with a voltage above their threshold voltage and a current below their rating.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Current and lifetime change greatly with a small change in applied voltage.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] They thus require a current-regulated supply (usually just a series resistor for indicator LEDs).
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Efficiency droop: The efficiency of LEDs decreases as the electric current increases.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Heating also increases with higher currents, which compromises LED lifetime.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] These effects put practical limits on the current through an LED in high power applications.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Unlike a traditional incandescent lamp, an LED will light only when voltage is applied in the forward direction of the diode.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] No current flows and no light is emitted if voltage is applied in the reverse direction.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] If the reverse voltage exceeds the breakdown voltage, which is typically about five volts, a large current flows and the LED will be damaged.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] If the reverse current is sufficiently limited to avoid damage, the reverse-conducting LED is a useful noise diode.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] By definition, the energy band gap of any diode is higher when reverse-biased than when forward-biased.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Because the band gap energy determines the wavelength of the light emitted, the color cannot be the same when reverse-biased.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] The reverse breakdown voltage is sufficiently high that the emitted wavelength cannot be similar enough to still be visible.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Though dual-LED packages exist that contain a different color LED in each direction, it is not expected that any single LED element can emit visible light when reverse-biased.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] It is not known if any zener diode could exist that emits light only in reverse-bias mode.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Uniquely, this type of LED would conduct when connected backwards.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] LED manufacturing involves multiple steps, including epitaxy, chip processing, chip separation, and packaging.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] In a typical LED manufacturing process, encapsulation is performed after probing, dicing, die transfer from wafer to package, and wire bonding or flip chip mounting, perhaps using indium tin oxide, a transparent electrical conductor.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] In this case, the bond wire(s) are attached to the ITO film that has been deposited in the LEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Flip chip circuit on board (COB) is a technique that can be used to manufacture LEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p01] Conventional LEDs are made from a variety of inorganic semiconductor materials.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The application of LEDs in horticulture has revolutionized plant cultivation by providing energy-efficient, customizable lighting solutions that optimize plant growth and development.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs offer precise control over light spectra, intensity, and photoperiods, enabling growers to tailor lighting conditions to the specific needs of different plant species and growth stages.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] This technology enhances photosynthesis, improves crop yields, and reduces energy costs compared to traditional lighting systems.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Additionally, LEDs generate less heat, allowing closer placement to plants without risking thermal damage, and contribute to sustainable farming practices by lowering carbon footprints and extending growing seasons in controlled environments.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Light spectrum affects growth, metabolite profile, and resistance against fungal phytopathogens of *Solanum lycopersicum* seedlings.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs can also be used in micropropagation.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The low energy consumption, low maintenance and small size of LEDs has led to uses as status indicators and displays on a variety of equipment and installations.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Large-area LED displays are used as stadium displays, dynamic decorative displays, and dynamic message signs on freeways.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Thin, lightweight message displays are used at airports and railway stations, and as destination displays for trains, buses, trams, and ferries.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] One-color light is well suited for traffic lights and signals, exit signs, emergency vehicle lighting, ships' navigation lights, and LED-based Christmas lights.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Because of their long life, fast switching times, and visibility in broad daylight due to their high output and focus, LEDs have been used in automotive brake lights and turn signals.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The use in brakes improves safety, due to a great reduction in the time needed to light fully, or faster rise time, about 200 milliseconds faster than an incandescent bulb.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] This gives drivers behind more time to react.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In a dual intensity circuit (rear markers and brakes) if the LEDs are not pulsed at a fast enough frequency, they can create a phantom array, where ghost images of the LED appear if the eyes quickly scan across the array.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] White LED headlamps are beginning to appear.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Using LEDs has styling advantages because LEDs can form much thinner lights than incandescent lamps with parabolic reflectors.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Due to the relative cheapness of low output LEDs, they are also used in many temporary uses such as glowsticks and throwies.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Artists have also used LEDs for LED art.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] With the development of high-efficiency and high-power LEDs, it has become possible to use LEDs in lighting and illumination.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] To encourage the shift to LED lamps and other high-efficiency lighting, in 2008 the US Department of Energy created the L Prize competition.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The Philips Lighting North America LED bulb won the first competition on August 3, 2011, after successfully completing 18 months of intensive field, lab, and product testing.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Efficient lighting is needed for sustainable architecture.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] As of 2011, some LED bulbs provide up to 150 lm/W and even inexpensive low-end models typically exceed 50 lm/W, so that a 6-watt LED could achieve the same results as a standard 40-watt incandescent bulb.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The lower heat output of LEDs also reduces demand on air conditioning systems.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Worldwide, LEDs are rapidly adopted to displace less effective sources such as incandescent lamps and CFLs and reduce electrical energy consumption and its associated emissions.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Solar powered LEDs are used as street lights and in architectural lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The mechanical robustness and long lifetime are used in automotive lighting on cars, motorcycles, and bicycle lights.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LED street lights are employed on poles and in parking garages.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In 2007, the Italian village of Torraca was the first place to convert its street lighting to LEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Cabin lighting on recent Airbus and Boeing jetliners uses LED lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs are also being used in airport and heliport lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LED airport fixtures currently include medium-intensity runway lights, runway centerline lights, taxiway centerline and edge lights, guidance signs, and obstruction lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs are also used as a light source for DLP projectors, and to backlight newer LCD television (referred to as LED TV), computer monitor (including laptop) and handheld device LCDs, succeeding older CCFL-backlit LCDs although being superseded by OLED screens.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] RGB LEDs raise the color gamut by as much as 45%.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Screens for TV and computer displays can be made thinner using LEDs for backlighting.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs are small, durable and need little power, so they are used in handheld devices such as flashlights.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LED strobe lights or camera flashes operate at a safe, low voltage, instead of the 250+ volts commonly found in xenon flashlamp-based lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] This is especially useful in cameras on mobile phones, where space is at a premium and bulky voltage-raising circuitry is undesirable.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs are used for infrared illumination in night vision uses including security cameras.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] A ring of LEDs around a video camera, aimed forward into a retroreflective background, allows chroma keying in video productions.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs are used in mining operations, as cap lamps to provide light for miners.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Research has been done to improve LEDs for mining, to reduce glare and to increase illumination, reducing risk of injury to the miners.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs are increasingly finding uses in medical and educational applications, for example as mood enhancement.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] NASA has even sponsored research for the use of LEDs to promote health for astronauts.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Light can be used to transmit data and analog signals.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] For example, lighting white LEDs can be used in systems assisting people to navigate in closed spaces while searching necessary rooms or objects.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Assistive listening devices in many theaters and similar spaces use arrays of infrared LEDs to send sound to listeners' receivers.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Light-emitting diodes (as well as semiconductor lasers) are used to send data over many types of fiber optic cable, from digital audio over TOSLINK cables to the very high bandwidth fiber links that form the Internet backbone.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] For some time, computers were commonly equipped with IrDA interfaces, which allowed them to send and receive data to nearby machines via infrared.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Because LEDs can cycle on and off millions of times per second, very high data bandwidth can be achieved.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] For that reason, visible light communication (VLC) has been proposed as an alternative to the increasingly competitive radio bandwidth.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] VLC operates in the visible part of the electromagnetic spectrum, so data can be transmitted without occupying the frequencies of radio communications.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Machine vision systems often require bright and homogeneous illumination, so features of interest are easier to process.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Barcode scanners are the most common example of machine vision applications, and many of those scanners use red LEDs instead of lasers.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Optical computer mice use LEDs as a light source for the miniature camera within the mouse.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs are useful for machine vision because they provide a compact, reliable source of light.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LED lamps can be turned on and off to suit the needs of the vision system, and the shape of the beam produced can be tailored to match the system's requirements.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The discovery of radiative recombination in aluminum gallium nitride (AlGaN) alloys by U.S.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) led to the conceptualization of UV light-emitting diodes (LEDs) to be incorporated in light-induced fluorescence sensors used for biological agent detection.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In 2004, the Edgewood Chemical Biological Center (ECBC) initiated the effort to create a biological detector named TAC-BIO.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The program capitalized on semiconductor UV optical sources (SUVOS) developed by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA).
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] UV-induced fluorescence is one of the most robust techniques used for rapid real-time detection of biological aerosols.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The first UV sensors were lasers lacking in-field-use practicality.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In order to address this, DARPA incorporated SUVOS technology to create a low-cost, small, lightweight, low-power device.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The TAC-BIO detector's response time was one minute from when it sensed a biological agent.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] It was also demonstrated that the detector could be operated unattended indoors and outdoors for weeks at a time.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Aerosolized biological particles fluoresce and scatter light under a UV light beam.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Observed fluorescence is dependent on the applied wavelength and the biochemical fluorophores within the biological agent.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] UV induced fluorescence offers a rapid, accurate, efficient and logistically practical way for biological agent detection.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] This is because the use of UV fluorescence is reagentless, or a process that does not require an added chemical to produce a reaction, with no consumables, or produces no chemical byproducts.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Additionally, TAC-BIO can reliably discriminate between threat and non-threat aerosols.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] It was claimed to be sensitive enough to detect low concentrations, but not so sensitive that it would cause false positives.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The particle-counting algorithm used in the device converted raw data into information by counting the photon pulses per unit of time from the fluorescence and scattering detectors, and comparing the value to a set threshold.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The original TAC-BIO was introduced in 2010, while the second-generation TAC-BIO GEN II, was designed in 2015 to be more cost-efficient, as plastic parts were used.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Its small, lightweight design allows it to be mounted to vehicles, robots, and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The second-generation device could also be utilized as an environmental detector to monitor air quality in hospitals, airplanes, or even in households to detect fungus and mold.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The light from LEDs can be modulated very quickly so they are used extensively in optical fiber and free-space optics communications.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] This includes remote controls, such as for television sets, where infrared LEDs are often used.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Opto-isolators use an LED combined with a photodiode or phototransistor to provide a signal path with electrical isolation between two circuits.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] An opto-isolator also lets information be transferred between circuits that do not share a common ground potential.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Many sensor systems rely on light as the signal source.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs are often ideal as a light source due to the requirements of the sensors.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The Nintendo Wii's sensor bar uses infrared LEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Pulse oximeters use them for measuring oxygen saturation.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Some flatbed scanners use arrays of RGB LEDs rather than the typical cold-cathode fluorescent lamp as the light source.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Having independent control of three illuminated colors allows the scanner to calibrate itself for more accurate color balance, and there is no need for warm-up.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Further, its sensors only need be monochromatic, since at any one time the page being scanned is only lit by one color of light.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Since LEDs can also be used as photodiodes, they can be used for both photo emission and detection.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] This could be used, for example, in a touchscreen that registers reflected light from a finger or stylus.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Many materials and biological systems are sensitive to, or dependent on, light.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Grow lights use LEDs to increase photosynthesis in plants, and bacteria and viruses can be removed from water and other substances using UV LEDs for sterilization.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs of certain wavelengths have also been used for light therapy treatment of neonatal jaundice and acne.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs have also been used as a medium-quality voltage reference in electronic circuits.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The forward voltage drop (about 1.7 V for a red LED or 1.2V for an infrared) can be used instead of a Zener diode in low-voltage regulators.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Red LEDs have the flattest I/V curve above the knee.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Nitride-based LEDs have a fairly steep I/V curve and are useless for this purpose.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Although LED forward voltage is far more current-dependent than a Zener diode, Zener diodes with breakdown voltages below 3 V are not widely available.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The progressive miniaturization of low-voltage lighting technology, such as LEDs and OLEDs, suitable to incorporate into low-thickness materials has fostered experimentation in combining light sources and wall covering surfaces for interior walls in the form of LED wallpaper.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] LEDs require optimized efficiency to hinge on ongoing improvements such as phosphor materials and quantum dots.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The process of down-conversion (the method by which materials convert more-energetic photons to different, less energetic colors) also needs improvement.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] For example, the red phosphors that are used today are thermally sensitive and need to be improved in that aspect so that they do not color shift and experience efficiency drop-off with temperature.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Red phosphors could also benefit from a narrower spectral width to emit more lumens and becoming more efficient at converting photons.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In addition, work remains to be done in the realms of current efficiency droop, color shift, system reliability, light distribution, dimming, thermal management, and power supply performance.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Early suspicions were that the LED droop was caused by elevated temperatures.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Scientists showed that temperature was not the root cause of efficiency droop.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The mechanism causing efficiency droop was identified in 2007 as Auger recombination, which was taken with mixed reaction.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] A 2013 study conclusively identified Auger recombination as the cause.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] A new family of LEDs are based on the semiconductors called perovskites.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In 2018, less than four years after their discovery, the ability of perovskite LEDs (PLEDs) to produce light from electrons already rivaled those of the best performing OLEDs.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] They have a potential for cost-effectiveness as they can be processed from solution, a low-cost and low-tech method, which might allow perovskite-based devices that have large areas to be made with extremely low cost.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The most up-to-date PLED devices have broken the performance barrier by shooting the EQE above 20%.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In 2018, Cao et al. and Lin et al. independently published two papers on developing perovskite LEDs with EQE greater than 20%, which made these two papers a mile-stone in PLED development.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Their device have similar planar structure, i.e. the active layer (perovskite) is sandwiched between two electrodes.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] To achieve a high EQE, they not only reduced non-radiative recombination, but also utilized their own, subtly different methods to improve the EQE.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In the work of Cao *et al.*, researchers targeted the outcoupling problem, which is that the optical physics of thin-film LEDs causes the majority of light generated by the semiconductor to be trapped in the device.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] To achieve this goal, they demonstrated that solution-processed perovskites can spontaneously form submicrometre-scale crystal platelets, which can efficiently extract light from the device.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] These perovskites are formed via the introduction of amino acid additives into the perovskite precursor solutions.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In addition, their method is able to passivate perovskite surface defects and reduce nonradiative recombination.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Therefore, by improving the light outcoupling and reducing nonradiative losses, Cao and his colleagues successfully achieved PLED with EQE up to 20.7%.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Lin and his colleague used a different approach to generate high EQE.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Instead of modifying the microstructure of perovskite layer, they chose to adopt a new strategy for managing the compositional distribution in the device—an approach that simultaneously provides high luminescence and balanced charge injection.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In other words, they still used flat emissive layer, but tried to optimize the balance of electrons and holes injected into the perovskite, so as to make the most efficient use of the charge carriers.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Moreover, in the perovskite layer, the crystals are perfectly enclosed by MABr additive (where MA is CH3NH3).
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] The MABr shell passivates the nonradiative defects that would otherwise be present perovskite crystals, resulting in reduction of the nonradiative recombination.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Therefore, by balancing charge injection and decreasing nonradiative losses, Lin and his colleagues developed PLED with EQE up to 20.3%.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Certain blue LEDs and cool-white LEDs can exceed safe limits of the so-called blue-light hazard as defined in eye safety specifications such as "ANSI/IESNA RP-27.1–05: Recommended Practice for Photobiological Safety for Lamp and Lamp Systems".
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] One study showed no evidence of a risk in normal use at domestic illuminance, and that caution is only needed for particular occupational situations or for specific populations.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In 2006, the International Electrotechnical Commission published *IEC 62471 Photobiological safety of lamps and lamp systems*, replacing the application of early laser-oriented standards for classification of LED sources.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] While LEDs have the advantage over fluorescent lamps, in that they do not contain mercury, they may contain other hazardous metals such as lead and arsenic.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] In 2016 the American Medical Association (AMA) issued a statement concerning the possible adverse influence of blueish street lighting on the sleep-wake cycle of city-dwellers.
[src:dali-lighting/light-emitting-diode-p02] Critics in the industry claim exposure levels are not high enough to have a noticeable effect.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] A **lighting control system** is intelligent network-based lighting control that incorporates communication between various system inputs and outputs related to lighting control with the use of one or more central computing devices.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Lighting control systems are widely used on both indoor and outdoor lighting of commercial, industrial, and residential spaces.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Lighting control systems are sometimes referred to under the term **smart lighting**.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Lighting control systems serve to provide the right amount of light where and when it is needed.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Lighting control systems are employed to maximize the energy savings from the lighting system, satisfy building codes, or comply with green building and energy conservation programs.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Lighting control systems may include a lighting technology designed for energy efficiency, convenience and security.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] This may include high efficiency fixtures and automated controls that make adjustments based on conditions such as occupancy or daylight availability.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Lighting is the deliberate application of light to achieve some aesthetic or practical effect (e.g. illumination of a security breach).
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] It includes task lighting, accent lighting, and general lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The term *lighting controls* is typically used to indicate stand-alone control of the lighting within a space.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] This may include occupancy sensors, timeclocks, and photocells that are hard-wired to control fixed groups of lights independently.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Adjustment occurs manually at each devices location.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The efficiency of and market for residential lighting controls has been characterized by the Consortium for Energy Efficiency.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The term *lighting control system* refers to an intelligent networked system of devices related to lighting control.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] These devices may include relays, occupancy sensors, photocells, light control switches or touchscreens, and signals from other building systems (such as fire alarm or HVAC).
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Adjustment of the system occurs both at device locations and at central computer locations via software programs or other interface devices.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The major advantage of a lighting control system over stand-alone lighting controls or conventional manual switching is the ability to control individual lights or groups of lights from a single user interface device.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] This ability to control multiple light sources from a user device allows complex lighting scenes to be created.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] A room may have multiple scenes pre-set, each one created for different activities in the room.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] A major benefit of lighting control systems is reduced energy consumption.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Longer lamp life is also gained when dimming and switching off lights when not in use.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Wireless lighting control systems provide additional benefits including reduced installation costs and increased flexibility over where switches and sensors may be placed.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Lighting applications represents 19% of the world's energy use and 6% of all greenhouse emissions.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] In the United States, 65 percent of energy consumption is used by commercial and industrial sectors, and 22 percent of this is used for lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Smart lighting enables households and users to remotely control cooling, heating, lighting and appliances, minimizing unnecessary light and energy use.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] This ability saves energy and provides a level of comfort and convenience.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] From outside the traditional lighting industry, the future success of lighting will require involvement of a number of stakeholders and stakeholder communities.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The concept of smart lighting also involves utilizing natural light from the sun to reduce the use of man-made lighting, and the simple concept of people turning off lighting when they leave a room.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] A smart lighting system can ensure that dark areas are illuminated when in use.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The lights actively respond to the activities of the occupants based on sensors and intelligence (logic) that anticipates the lighting needs of an occupant.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] This can enhance comfort, improve safety, reduce manual effort, and improve energy efficiency.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Lights can be used to dissuade those from areas they should not be.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] A security breach, for example, is an event that could trigger floodlights at the breach point.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Preventative measures include illuminating key access points (such as walkways) at night and automatically adjusting the lighting when a household is away to make it appear as though there are occupants.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Chronological time schedules incorporate specific times of the day, week, month or year.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Solar time schedules incorporate sunrise and sunset times, often used to switch outdoor lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Solar time scheduling requires that the location of the building be set.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] This is accomplished using the building's geographic location via either latitude and longitude or by picking the nearest city in a given database giving the approximate location and corresponding solar times.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Space occupancy is primarily determined with occupancy sensors.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Smart lighting that utilizes occupancy sensors can work in unison with other lighting connected to the same network to adjust lighting per various conditions.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The table below shows potential electricity savings from using occupancy sensors to control lighting in various types of spaces.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The advantages of ultrasonic devices are that they are sensitive to all types of motion and generally there are zero coverage gaps, since they can detect movements not within the line of sight.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Electric lighting energy use can be adjusted by automatically dimming and/or switching electric lights in response to the level of available daylight.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Reducing the amount of electric lighting used when daylight is available is known as daylight harvesting.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] In response to daylighting technology, daylight-linked automated response systems have been developed to further reduce energy consumption.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] These technologies are helpful, but they do have their downfalls.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Many times, rapid and frequent switching of the lights on and off can occur, particularly during unstable weather conditions or when daylight levels are changing around the switching illuminance.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Not only does this disturb occupants, it can also reduce lamp life.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] A variation of this technology is the 'differential switching' or 'dead-band' photoelectric control which has multiple illuminances it switches from to reduce occupants being disturbed.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Alarm conditions typically include inputs from other building systems such as the fire alarm or HVAC system, which may trigger an emergency 'all lights on' or ' all lights flashing' command for example.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Program logic can tie all of the above elements together using constructs such as if-then-else statements and logical operators.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI) is specified in the IEC 62386 standard.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The use of automatic light dimming is an aspect of smart lighting that serves to reduce energy consumption.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Manual light dimming also has the same effect of reducing energy use.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] A complete sensor consists of a motion detector, an electronic control unit, and a controllable switch/relay.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The detector senses motion and determines whether there are occupants in the space.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] It also has a timer that signals the electronic control unit after a set period of inactivity.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The control unit uses this signal to activate the switch/relay to turn equipment on or off.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] For lighting applications, there are three main sensor types: passive infrared, ultrasonic, and hybrid.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Motion-detecting (microwave), heating-sensing (infrared), and sound-sensing; optical cameras, infrared motion, optical trip wires, door contact sensors, thermal cameras, micro radars, daylight sensors.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] In the 1980s there was a strong requirement to make commercial lighting more controllable so that it could become more energy efficient.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Initially this was done with analog control, allowing fluorescent ballasts and dimmers to be controlled from a central source.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] This was a step in the right direction, but cabling was complicated and therefore not cost effective.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Tridonic was an early company to go digital with their broadcast protocols, DSI, in 1991.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] DSI was a basic protocol as it transmitted one control value to change the brightness of all the fixtures attached to the line.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] What made this protocol more attractive, and able to compete with the established analog option, was the simple wiring.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] In production lighting 0-10V system was replaced by analog multiplexed systems such as D54 and AMX192, which themselves have been almost completely replaced by DMX512.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] For dimmable fluorescent lamps (where it operates instead at 1-10 V, where 1 V is minimum and 0 V is off) the system is being replaced by DSI, which itself is in the process of being replaced by DALI.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Those are all wired lighting control systems.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] There are also wireless lighting control systems that are based on some standard protocols like MIDI, ZigBee, Bluetooth Mesh, and others.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The standard for digital addressable lighting interface, mostly in professional and commercial deployments, is IEC 62386-104.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] This standard specifies the underlying technologies, which in wireless are VEmesh, which operates in the industrial Sub-1 GHz frequency band and Bluetooth Mesh, which operates in the 2.4 GHz frequency band.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The new type of control for lighting system is using Bluetooth connection directly to the lighting system.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] It is recently introduced by Philips HUE and company new name as Signify formerly known as Philips Lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] This system will need a smartphone or tablet where the user can install a special Philips Hue Bluetooth app.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The Bluetooth bulbs don't need a Philips Hue bridge to function.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] There is no need to have a Wi-Fi or data connection for controlling the lights with that system.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Smart lighting systems can be controlled using the internet to adjust lighting brightness and schedules.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] One technology involves a smart lighting network that assigns IP addresses to light bulbs.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Schubert predicts that revolutionary lighting systems will provide an entirely new means of sensing and broadcasting information.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] By blinking far too rapidly for any human to notice, the light will pick up data from sensors and carry it from room to room, reporting such information as the location of every person within a high-security building.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] A major focus of the Future Chips Constellation is smart lighting, a revolutionary new field in photonics based on efficient light sources that are fully tunable in terms of such factors as spectral content, emission pattern, polarization, color temperature, and intensity.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Architectural lighting control systems can integrate with a theater's on-off and dimmer controls, and are often used for house lights and stage lighting, and can include worklights, rehearsal lighting, and lobby lighting.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Control stations can be placed in several locations in the building and range in complexity from single buttons that bring up preset options-looks, to in-wall or desktop LCD touchscreen consoles.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Much of the technology is related to residential and commercial lighting control systems.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The benefit of architectural lighting control systems in the theater is the ability for theater staff to turn worklights and house lights on and off without having to use a lighting control console.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Alternately, the light designer can control these same lights with light cues from the lighting control console so that, for instance, the transition from houselights being up before a show starts and the first light cue of the show is controlled by one system.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The function of a traditional emergency lighting system is the supply of a minimum illuminating level when a line voltage failure appears.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Therefore, emergency lighting systems have to store energy in a battery module to supply lamps in case of failure.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] In this kind of lighting systems the internal damages, for example battery overcharging, damaged lamps and starting circuit failure must be detected and repaired by specialist workers.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] For this reason, the smart lighting prototype can check its functional state every fourteen days and dump the result into a LED display.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] With these features they can test themselves checking their functional state and displaying their internal damages.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Also the maintenance cost can be decreased.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The main idea is the substitution of the simple line voltage sensing block that appears in the traditional systems by a more complex one based on a microcontroller.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] This new circuit will assume the functions of line voltage sensing and inverter activation, by one side, and the supervision of all the system: lamp and battery state, battery charging, external communications, correct operation of the power stage, etc., by the other side.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The system has a great flexibility, for instance, it would be possible the communication of several devices with a master computer, which would know the state of each device all the time.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] A new emergency lighting system based on an intelligent module has been developed.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The micro-controller as a control and supervision device guarantees increase in the installation security and a maintenance cost saving.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Another important advantage is the cost saving for mass production specially whether a microcontroller with the program in ROM memory is used.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The advances achieved in photonics are already transforming society just as electronics revolutionized the world in recent decades and it will continue to contribute more in the future.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] From the statistics, North America's optoelectronics market grew to more than $20 billion in 2003.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] The LED (light-emitting diode) market is expected to reach $5 billion in 2007, and the solid-state lighting market is predicted to be $50 billion in 15–20 years, as stated by E.
[src:dali-lighting/lighting-control-system] Fred Schubert, Wellfleet Senior Distinguished Professor of the Future Chips Constellation at Rensselaer.
